> 
>     * most users install wheels, where astropy is compiled within some CI/docker image for each platform. I don't know what flags are used here, since the compilation logs are not shown in the wheels jobs (e.g. https://github.com/astropy/astropy/actions/runs/8182690920/job/22374432742#step:7:297). Could a good idea to make cibuildwheel more verbose and check the flags.

Since the wheels are built for specific CPU architecture and OS, it might be possible to specify the architecture through `CFLAGS` and that could be the minimum instruction set supported (e.g., OSX + ARM implies at least ARMV8, since the ARMV8 M1 is the first CPU that matches those specs). Though not sure that it will be worthwhile given that performance is not.a primary consideration for astropy. 

> 
>     * when installing from source and compiling locally, AFAIK the compilation flags are inherited by setuptools/distutils from the flags used to compile the Python you're using (I think from `sysconfig.get_config_vars("CFLAGS")`).
> 

It should be possible to add compiler flags through the extra_compile_args right? My understanding is that those flags are whatever was used to compile `python` with, and those tend to be on the conservative side (i.e., no more than `-O2`).


>     * for SIMD optimizations (`-ftree-vectorize`), this cannot be used in wheels since the same wheel will be installed on many different CPU architectures. Well it's possible and Numpy does it but using some runtime detection of CPU capabilities (https://pypackaging-native.github.io/key-issues/simd_support/), which is too complex for us and the little amount of C code we have (and that doesn't use SIMD instructions anyway). So to benefit from the best performance with our C code and SIMD optimizations with `-ftree-vectorize` it's necessary to install from source, overriding  the compilation flags if necessary (e.g. `CFLAGS='-O3 -march=native -ftree-vectorize' pip install -e . -v`). Could be interesting to benchmark the difference with sigma clipping.

`-O3` is effectively `-O2 -ftree-vectorize`. You don't need to have SIMD code in the C code - the `-march` dictates what instructions the compiler will generate. For example,  by default, gcc will emit the  128-bit vector instructions (SSE) from the early 2000's even though 512-bit vector instructions (AVX512) have been around for nearly 7 years now. One thing to do could be to add a README note recommending compiling from source for users (perhaps naming specific sub-packages that rely on C code) that might want a faster astropy. 

Thanks for the link on the simd_support within python packages. While reading that I realise that there is one option missing from that list - using the GCC `target_clones` [function attribute](https://gcc.gnu.org/onlinedocs/gcc/Common-Function-Attributes.html#index-target_005fclones-function-attribute). This should automatically create function multi-versioning and runtime dispatch - though I suspect this would still require the actual function line to be within multiple `#ifdef` conditions for each targeted OS + ISA (e.g., DARWIN + PPC64, DARWIN + x86_64, DARWIN + ARM etc...). 

On a completely unrelated note, while looking at the cibuildwheel logs I noticed that votable validation is printing [warnings](https://github.com/astropy/astropy/actions/runs/8182690920/job/22374435440#step:7:688) but in the end reporting that [all validation passed](https://github.com/astropy/astropy/actions/runs/8182690920/job/22374435440#step:7:928). Is that expected?","reactions":{"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/astropy/astropy/issues/comments/1983322601/reactions","total_count":0,"+1":0,"-1":0,"laugh":0,"hooray":0,"confused":0,"heart":0,"rocket":0,"eyes":0},"performed_via_github_app":null}}

